{"title_page": "List of Portuguese exonyms", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:G\u00eaneros de nomes de pa\u00edses em l\u00edngua portuguesa.png|thumb|400px|Genders of country names in Portuguese: male (green), female (purple) and neutral (yellow)]]\nBelow is a list of [[Portuguese language]] [[exonym]]s for places in non-Portuguese-speaking areas of [[Europe]] and the [[Maghreb]]. Some of them are used exclusively in [[European Portuguese]] (marked PT) while others appear just in [[Brazilian Portuguese]] (marked BR).\n\nSome of these terms are becoming disused, being often replaced with others closer to the original spelling. [[Loanword|Adoptions of foreign terms]] and names in general are more acceptable and easy to enter popular use in the Brazilian variety, with [[spelling pronunciation]]s or not.\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Albania - Alb\u00e2nia==\n\n*[[Shkod\u00ebr]] - Esc\u00fatare (archaic spelling)\n*[[Tirana|Tiran\u00eb]] - Tirana\n\n==Austria - \u00c1ustria==\n\n*[[Danube]] - Dan\u00fabio\n*[[Innsbruck]] - Insbruque (archaic)\n*[[Karnten]] - Car\u00edntia\n*[[Salzburg]] - Salzburgo, Salisburgo (rare)\n*[[Steiermark]] - Est\u00edria\n*[[Vienna]] - Viena\n\n==Belarus - Belarus, Bielorr\u00fassia (archaic)==\n\n*[[Minsk]] - Minsque (rare)\n\n==Belgium - B\u00e9lgica==\n\n*[[Antwerp]]en - Antu\u00e9rpia\n*[[Province of Brabant|Brabant]] - Brabante\n*[[Bruges]] - Bruges\n*[[Brussels]] - Bruxelas\n*[[Ghent]] - Gante\n*[[Leuven]] - Lovaina\n*[[Meuse (river)|Maas]] - Mosa (PT)\n*[[Scheldt]] - Escalda\n*[[Flanders]] - Flandres\n*[[Wallonia]] - Val\u00f3nia (PT), Val\u00f4nia (BR)\n\n==Bosnia and Herzegovina - B\u00f3snia e Herzegovina==\n\n*[[Sarajevo]] - Saraievo\n\n==Bulgaria - Bulg\u00e1ria==\n\n*[[Sofia]] - S\u00f3fia\n\n==Croatia - Cro\u00e1cia==\n\n*[[Zagreb]] - Zagrebe\n\n==Cyprus - Chipre==\n\n*[[Limassol|Lemesos/Limasol]] - Limassol\n*[[Nicosia]] - Nic\u00f3sia\n*[[Paphos]] - Pafos\n\n==Czech Republic/Czechia - Rep\u00fablica C