lank1_name_sec1        = [[List of cities in Ukraine by subdivision#Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast|Cities]] <small>(total)</small>\n| blank1_info_sec1        = 15\n| blank2_name_sec1        = \u2022&nbsp;[[City of regional significance (Ukraine)|Regional cities]]\n| blank2_info_sec1        = 6\n| blank3_name_sec1        = [[List of urban-type settlements in Ukraine by subdivision#Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast|{{nowrap|Urban-type settlements}}]]\n| blank3_info_sec1        = 24\n| blank4_name_sec1        = Villages\n| blank4_info_sec1        = 477<ref>That includes rural councils which may have several villages or rural settlements (selyshcha).</ref><ref>[http://gska2.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/A005?rdat1=09.11.2008&rf7571=13163 Subdivision listings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521221848/http://gska2.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/A005?rdat1=09.11.2008&rf7571=13163 |date=2011-05-21 }} {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n| timezone1               = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +3\n| postal_code_type        = [[Ukrainian postal codes|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = 88-90xxx\n| area_code_type          = [[Area code#Ukraine|Area code]]\n| area_code               = [[Area code#Ukraine|+380-34]]\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:UA|UA-26]]\n| registration_plate_type = [[Vehicle registration plates of Ukraine|Vehicle registration]]\n| registration_plate      = AT, KT\n| blank_name_sec2         = [[FIPS 10-4]]\n| blank_info_sec2         = [[List of FIPS region codes (S-U)#UP:Ukraine|UP06]]\n| website                 = [http://www.if.gov.ua www.if.gov.ua]<br/>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071001062059/http://gska2.rada.gov.ua:7777/pls/z7502/A005?rdat1=04.06.2007&rf7571=13163 www.rada.gov.ua]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast''' ({{lang-uk|\u0406\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e-\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c}}, [[Romanization of Ukrainian|translit.]] ''Ivano-Frankivs\u2019ka oblast\u2019'' or formerly as '''Stanislavshchyna''' or '''Stanislavivshchyna''' \u2013 ''[[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]'': ''\u0421\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0430'' or ''\u0421\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0456\u0432\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0430'') is an [[administrative divisions of Ukraine|oblast]] (region) in [[western Ukraine]]. Its [[administrative center]] is the city of [[Ivano-Frankivsk]]. As is the case with most other oblasts of [[Ukraine]] this region has the same name as its administrative center \u2013 which was renamed by the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Ukrainian authorities]] after the Ukrainian writer [[Ivan Franko]] on November 9, 1962. Population: {{Ua-pop-est2016|1,382,352}}.\n\nIvano-Frankivsk Oblast is also known to Ukrainians by a deep-rooted alternative name: ''[[Prykarpattia]]'' (although some sources may also consider the southern [[Lviv Oblast]] including such cities as [[Stryi]], [[Truskavets]], and [[Drohobych]], as also part of Prykarpattia).{{Citation needed|date=September 2012}}  Prykarpattia, together with [[Lviv Oblast|Lviv]] and [[Ternopil Oblast|Ternopil]] regions, was the main body of the historic region of eastern [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Halychyna]]; which in the 13th century was a part of the Kingdom of Rus and the Halych-Volyn Principality (see [[Kingdom of Galicia\u2013Volhynia]]). Along with the Lviv and Ternopil regions ''Prykarpattia'' is a component of the [[Carpathian Euroregion]].\n\nDuring the times of the [[Second Polish Republic]] the area was known as [[Stanis\u0142aw\u00f3w Voivodeship]] (1918\u20131939) and later, after the [[Soviet invasion of Poland]], as '''Stanislav Oblast''' (1939\u20131962). During [[World War II]] it was part of the [[District of Galicia]] in [[General Governorate]]. Until the 20th century the major center of the region was the city of [[Kolomyia]] (which is a major cultural center of [[Pokuttya]], the traditional name for the southern part of the oblast).\n\n==Name==\nAs with the rest of Ukraine's oblasts Ivano-Frankivsk may also be known by its matronymical name ''Ivano-Frankivshchyna''. However, that name did not receive general public acceptance and commonly Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast is almost always called ''[[Prykarpattya]]'' \u2013 a historic name for the same region. (Geographically the historic region covers a much larger portion of Ukraine than just the Ivano-Frankivsk region.)\n\n==Geography==\nIvano-Frankivsk Oblast borders [[Lviv Oblast]] to its north and west, [[Zakarpattya Oblast]] to its south-west, has a 50-km long state border with [[Romania]] ([[Maramure\u0219 County]]) to its immediate south, and it borders [[Chernivtsi Oblast]] to the south-east and [[Ternopil Oblast]] to the east. It is situated partly in the [[Eastern European Plain]] and partly [[Carpathian Foothills (Ukraine)|Carpathian Foothills]]. The oblast may be divided into three regions: mountainous, pre-mountainous, and plains.\n\nThe climate is mildly-continental and damp with cool summers and mild winters. The average monthly temperature in June is {{convert|18|C|F|0}} with {{convert|12|to|16|C|F|0}} in the mountains. The average monthly temperature in January is {{convert|-4|C|F|0}} with {{convert|-6|C|F|0}} in the mountains. Average precipitation varies annually around {{convert|650|mm|1|abbr=on}}  with {{convert|1550|mm|0|abbr=on}} in the mountains.\n\n===Relief===\n{{see also|Divisions of the Carpathians}}\n[[File:Ukraine geology.png|300px|thumb|Geology of Ukraine]]\nThe region is situated between two main regional tectonic plates: Carpathian fold belt and Volhynia-Podillya plate. The most prominent features of the first one are the [[Carpathian Mountains]], while the second one - [[Dniester]] river.\n\nThe Carpathian Mountains contribute tremendously to the change in relief of Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast and their elevation rises from north-east to south-west stretching along the oblast's south-western border. The elevation of the oblast varies from 230m to 2,061m [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]]. The mountains occupy almost one half of the whole Oblast and consist of two main mountain ranges: the [[Gorgany]] (highest peak \u2013 Mt. Syvulya Major (1,836m)) and the [[Chornohora]] range (highest peak \u2013 Mt. [[Hoverla]] (2,061m)).\n\nThe rest of Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast is located within the [[Dniester|Dniester river]] and [[Prut|Prut river]] valleys. The plains of the oblast are part of the [[Carpathian Foothills (Ukraine)|Carpathian Foothills]] and [[Opillia Upland]] (part of [[Podolian Upland|Podillia Upland]]) which are cut through by [[Dniester]]. The [[Highland (geography)|upland]] has a temperate-climate habitat mixed with [[grassland]] and [[woodland]] \u2013 also known as the [[forest steppe]]. The relief of the region consists mostly of [[rolling hill]]s of 230-400m over the sea level. Near river valleys are common [[canyon]]s and [[ravine]]s.\n\n{{main|Opillia Upland}}\nThe Dniester flows mainly through the [[Halych Raion]] and along the administrative border between Ivano-Frankivsk and [[Ternopil Oblast]]s. The territory of the region within immediate proximity to the river is traditionally known as ''Opillia''. Opillia, however, stretches far beyond the oblast and only covers two of its raions: [[Halych Raion]] and [[Rohatyn Raion]], both located in the north. Relief in the area consists of rolling hills uplands.\n\n{{main|Carpathian Foothills (Ukraine)}}\nThe Carpathian foothills consist mostly of low denudation accumulative uplands, while the right bank of Dniester along the border with the [[Ternopil Oblast]] depicts [[karst]] type relief of [[Pokuttia Upland]]. Because of it near that area along [[Dniester]] relief shows forms of [[canyon]]. Pokuttia Upland between [[Bystrytsia of Nadvirna]] and [[Prut River]] (Prut-Bystrytsia Upland) serves as drainage divide within the oblast between Dniester and Prut. Carpathian foothills have two depressions: one is at the confluence of [[Bystrytsia of Solotvyn]], [[Bystrytsia of Nadvirna]], [[Vorona River (Bystrytsia)|Vorona]] and [[Bystrytsia River|Bystrytsia]] rivers, called Bystrytsia Depression, and another is around the city of [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]], called Kalush Depression.\n\n===Hydrology===\n{{main|Rivers in Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast}}\nOblast has plethora of rivers, waterfalls, mountainous brooks, and smaller ponds, but there is almost no other type of bodies of water such as lakes and water reservoirs. Most of rivers either flow into [[Dniester]] or [[Prut River]] (tributary of [[Danube]]). The total water drainage area of the region is {{convert|13900|km\u00b2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. Segments of Dniester and [[Cheremosh River]] are used as administrative borders with [[Ternopil Oblast|Ternopil]] and [[Chernivtsi Oblast|Chernivtsi]] oblasts respectfully.\n\nThe water drainage divide between Dniester and Prut cuts the region through middle of following districts: [[Nadvirna Raion]], [[Kolomyia Raion]], [[Tlumach Raion]], and [[Horodenka Raion]].\n\n===Nature Sanctuaries===\nThe region is a home to some 456 preserved areas (on June 1, 2006) of some {{convert|195,633|ha|acre|abbr=on}}, 30 out of which are of all-national importance with an area of {{convert|108,742|ha|acre|abbr=on}} and the rest of a local importance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.orada.if.ua/fileadmin/documents/Programi/215-9.pdf |title=Tourism in the Ivano-Frankivsk Region (government website) |access-date=2011-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007161332/http://www.orada.if.ua/fileadmin/documents/Programi/215-9.pdf |archive-date=2011-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the Ivano-Frankivsk Region is located a strict nature reserve Gorgany that was created in 1996. There are five [[national park]]s in the region. There are numerous natural monuments of feature and habitat management areas ([[zakaznik]]s).\n\n{| class=toccolours\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:275px;\"| Park !! District\n|-\n| [[Carpathian National Nature Park]]\n | Verkhovyna / Nadvirna\n|-\n| [[National Nature Park Hutsulshchyna]] || Verkhovyna\n|-\n| [[Halych National Nature Park]] || Halych\n|-\n| [[Verkhovyna National Nature Park]] || Verkhovyna\n|-\n| [[National Nature Park Synyohora]] || Bohorodchany\n|}\n\n{| class=toccolours\n|- align=left\n! style=\"width:275px;\"| Nature Preserve !! District\n|-\n| [[Nature Preserve Gorgany]]\n | Nadvirna\n|}\n\n==Government==\n{{see also|Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast local election, 2010}}\nThe government in the region is headed by the chairman of the regional state administration (for simplicity sake - governor) appointed by the [[President of Ukraine]]. The governor appoints his deputies forming his regional governing cabinet to supervise the government policies in the region. Aside of the state administration the region has its own council that is headed by its chairman. The composition of the council depends on the popular vote in the region, while the chairman is elected within the elected council.\n;Regional State Administration\nRegional State Administration consists of the chairman and his deputies (5) supported by the \"aparat\" of the administration. Within the administration are numerous departments, each of them headed by a chief of department. The Ivano-Frankivsk Region State Administration has 17 departments and other government institutions such as the Children Service, regional state archives, and others.\n\n* Office of State Administration\n* Chief Department of Economy\n* Chief Financial Department\n* Chief Department industry and infrastructure development\n* Chief Department of tourism, Euro-integration, foreign relations, and investments\n* Chief Department of legal and interior policies\n* Chief Department of family, youth, and sports\n* Chief Department of labor and social security\n* Department of culture\n* Chief Department of agro-industrial development\n* Chief Department of regional development and construction\n* Department of communal management\n* Department of urban development and architecture\n* Chief Department of Education and Science\n* Chief Department of Health Security\n* Department of Extraordinary Situation and Protection of Population from Consequences of the Chornobyl Catastrophe\n* Media Department\n* Department of resources and management support\n* Children Service\n* Inspection of the State Technical Supervision\n* Inspection of quality and formation of resources of agricultural products\n* State Archives of the Region\n* Ivano-Frankivsk regional center for preparation and improving the qualification of workers of bodies of state power, bodies of local self-governing, state enterprises, institutions, and organizations\n;Regional council\n{{bar box\n|title=Seats and percentage\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=320px\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Freedom\"|Svoboda]] (17)|DarkBlue|14.90}}\n{{bar percent|[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Fatherland]] (16)|Crimson|14.00}}\n{{bar percent|[[Our Ukraine (political party)|Our Ukraine]] (15)|Orange|13.20}}\n{{bar percent|[[Front of Changes]] (13)|Brown|11.40}}\n{{bar percent|[[Party of Regions]] (11)|Steelblue|9.60}}\n{{bar percent|Ukrainian Party (11)|Olive|9.60}}\n{{bar percent|[[People's Party (Ukraine)|People's Party]] (9)|SpringGreen|7.90}}\n{{bar percent|Revival (5)|DarkGreen|4.40}}\n{{bar percent|[[Ukrainian People's Party]] (5)|LightGrey|4.40}}\n{{bar percent|[[Ukrainian Republican Party \"Sobor\"|Cathedral]] (4)|Grey|3.50}}\n{{bar percent|[[People's Movement of Ukraine|RUKh]] (3)|Pink|2.60}}\n{{bar percent|[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]] (2)|Indigo|1.80}}\n{{bar percent|[[For Ukraine!]] (1)|Green|0.90}}\n}}\n*Chairman: Oleksandr Sych ([[All-Ukrainian Union \"Freedom\"|Svoboda]])\n\n==Regional Subdivisions==\n{{main|Administrative divisions of Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast}}\n\n===Primary divisions===\nThe Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast is administratively subdivided into 14 [[district]]s ([[raions]]) as well as 6 cities ([[municipality|municipalities]]) which represent a separate raion and in direct subordination to the regional government, among which are [[Bolekhiv]], [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]], [[Kolomyya]], [[Yaremche]], and the administrative center of the region, [[Ivano-Frankivsk]]. [[Burshtyn]] became the 6th city of regional importance in 2014. The formation of the region was established in 1921 in the [[Second Polish Republic]] and was in majority preserved during the Soviet times. Most of the districts (former powiats) were reestablished as well in 1960s. The major industrial and cultural centers of the region were given a wider form of autonomy and assigned as the cities of regional subordination.\n\n{| border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left; border:1px solid #ddd; font-size:90%;\" summary=\"Districts of the Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast and their centers\"\n|+ style=\"background:#ddd; vertical-align:bottom; text-align:left; font-size:111%; font-weight:bold; padding:.5em 0;\" | Raions of the Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n! || style=\"text-align:left; font-weight:normal;\" | No.\n! style=\"text-align:left; font-weight:normal;\" | Name <br> Created\n! style=\"text-align:left; font-weight:normal;\" | [[Coat of arms|COA]]\n! style=\"text-align:left; font-weight:normal;\" | Administrative Center <br> Type\n! style=\"text-align:left; font-weight:normal;\" | Area (km<sup>2</sup> / sq mi) <br> Population (2001)\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || 1\n| [[Bohorodchany Raion]] <br> January 1, 1947\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Bohorodchany gerb.png|20px]]\n| [[Bohorodchany]] <br/>''(Urban-type settlement)''\n| {{convert|799|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 70,212\n| rowspan=\"15\" |[[File:Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast.jpg|300px|Raions of the Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast]]\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| || 2\n| [[Verkhovyna Raion]] <br> December 8, 1966\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Verkhovyna's herb.jpg|30px]]\n| [[Verkhovyna]] <br/>''(Urban-type settlement)''\n| {{convert|1254|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 30,079\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || 3\n| [[Halych Raion]] <br> January 1, 1947\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of Arms Halych.PNG|35px]]\n| [[Halych]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|723|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 65,640\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| || 4\n| [[Horodenka Raion]] <br> January 1, 1947\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:COA of Horodenka.png|25px]]\n| [[Horodenka]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|747|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 60,881\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || 5\n| [[Dolyna Raion]] <br> January 1, 1947\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of Arms of Dolyna.svg|25px]]\n| [[Dolyna]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|1248|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 71,059\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; \n| || 6\n| [[Kalush Raion]] <br> January 1, 1947\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:UKR \u041a\u0430\u0301\u043b\u0443\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u0301\u043d COA.gif|25px]]\n| [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|647|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 62,883\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || 7\n| [[Kolomyia Raion]] <br> January 1, 1947\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of Arms of Kolomyia.svg|20px]]\n| [[Kolomyia]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|1026|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 105,940\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; \n| || 8\n| [[Kosiv Raion]] <br> January 1, 1947\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Kos\u00f3w COA.png|25px]]\n| [[Kosiv]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|903|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 90,167\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || 9\n| [[Nadvirna Raion]] <br> January 4, 1965\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Nadvirna COA.png|25px]]\n| [[Nadvirna]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|1294|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 113,508\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; \n| || 10\n| [[Rohatyn Raion]] <br> January 4, 1965\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of Arms of Rohatyn.svg|20px]]\n| [[Rohatyn]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|815|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 51,125\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || 11\n| [[Rozhniativ Raion]] <br> January 4, 1965\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of arms of Rozhniativ Raion.gif|25px]]\n| [[Rozhniativ]] <br/>''(Urban-type settlement)''\n| {{convert|1303|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 75,598\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; \n| || 12\n| [[Sniatyn Raion]] <br> January 4, 1965\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Sniatyn coa IIRP.png|20px]]\n| [[Sniatyn]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|602|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 68,971\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || 13\n| [[Tysmenytsia Raion]] <br> December 8, 1966\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Tysmenic coa.png|25px]]\n| [[Tysmenytsia]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|736|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 85,400\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; \n| || 14\n| [[Tlumach Raion]] <br> January 4, 1965\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Tlumach coat of arms.svg|20px]]\n| [[Tlumach]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|684|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 52,835\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| ||\n|\n|\n| '''Average'''\n| '''{{convert|912.9|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 71,735.6'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#ddd; text-align:left; font-size:111%; font-weight:bold; padding:.5em 0;\" | Main city municipalities of the Ivano-Frankivsk Region\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| || a\n| [[Bolekhiv]] <br> October 21, 1993\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of arms of Bolekhiv.png|20px]]\n| [[Bolekhiv]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|300|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 21,232\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| || b\n| [[Ivano-Frankivsk]] <br> October 28, 1963\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Ivano-Frankivsk Coat of Arms.png|30px]]\n| [[Ivano-Frankivsk]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|84|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 230,443\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| || c\n| [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]] <br> March 20, 1972\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of Arms of Kalush.svg|25px]]\n| [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|65|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 67,887\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| || d\n| [[Kolomyia]] <br> October 28, 1963\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of Arms of Kolomyia.svg|20px]]\n| [[Kolomyia]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|41|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 61,448\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| || e\n| [[Yaremche]] <br> December 30, 1977\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Yaremche coa.png|20px]]\n| [[Yaremche]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|657|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 20,821\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| || f\n| [[Burshtyn]] <br> March 11, 2014\n| align=\"center\"  | [[File:Coat of Arms of Burshtyn.svg|20px]]\n| [[Burshtyn]] <br/>''(City)''\n| {{convert|657|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 20,821\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| ||\n|\n|\n| '''Total'''\n| '''{{convert|1147|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} <br> 401,831 (27.6%)'''\n|}\n\n===Secondary divisions===\n;City municipalities (councils)/mayors\nThe oblast has 15 cities which are (alphabetical order): [[Bolekhiv]], [[Burshtyn]], [[Dolyna]], [[Halych]], [[Horodenka]], [[Ivano-Frankivsk]], [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]], [[Kolomyia]], [[Kosiv]], [[Nadvirna]], [[Rohatyn]], [[Sniatyn]], [[Tlumach]], [[Tysmenytsia]], and [[Yaremche]]. Five of those cities are of regional importance and the other ten are of district importance. All cities have its own council and mayor that represent a local form of self-government allowed by the laws on local administration and the [[Constitution of Ukraine]]. City municipalities of the region are independent from any district administration.\n;Town municipalities (councils)\nWithin the region there are 24 urbanized settlements (towns) which are a special settlement classification inherited from the Soviet municipal organization. Three of those towns serve as administrative centers of their respective districts. Each town has its own council that along with surrounding village councils compose a district administration which has its own executive branch, District State Administration, appointed by the [[President of Ukraine]]. Towns do not have a mayoral office and their head of the council serves as the main representative of the whole settlement. \n;Village municipalities (councils)\nAll other settlements in the region are considered rural and accounted for some 765 localities including villages and 20 selyshches (smaller villages) which are administered by 477 village councils. Some village municipalities consist of several villages, while others are a single-village municipality. There are several villages that are part of city municipalities such as Ivano-Frankivsk, Bolekhiv, and Yaremcha, while all others are spread out across the districts of the region.\n\n===Historical overview of subdivisions===\nWhen on November 27, 1939 the Soviet regime was established in [[Stanis\u0142aw\u00f3w Voivodeship]], the Polish administrative division of it was kept almost the same until January 17, 1940. Only two powiats Stryi and Zydaczow were transferred away.\n\nOn December 4, 1939 the voivodeship was officially renamed into Stanislav Oblast. In 1940 the oblast was redivided into 37 raions and two municipalities (cities of oblast subordination). The administrative centers of the former raions were following settlements: Bohorodchany (town), Bolekhiv (city), Bilshivtsi (town), Bukachivtsi (village), Burshtyn (town), Voinylov (village), Vyhoda (village), Halych (town), Hvizdets (town), Horodenka (town), Delyatyn (town), Dolyna (city), [[Verkhovyna|Zhabie]] (village), [[Yezupil|Zhovten]] (town), Zabolotiv (town), Kalush (city), Kolomyia (city), Korshiv (village), Kosiv (city), Kuty (town), Lanchyn (town), Lysets (town), Nadvirna (city), Novytsya (village), Obertyn (town), Otynya (town), Pechenizhyn (town), Rohatyn (city), Rozhnyativ (town), Snyatyn (city), Solotvyn (town), Stanislav (city), Tlumach (city), Tysmenytsya (town), Chernelytsya (town), Yabluniv (town), Yaremcha (village). Two municipalities were cities of Stanislav and Kolomyia. On November 11, 1940 Delyatyn Raion was liquidated. On November 16, 1940 Novytsya Raion was re-administrated under town of Perehinske.\n\nDuring the World War II the region was occupied by the [[Nazi Germany]] (see [[Operation Barbarossa]]). Along with Lviv, Drohobych and Tarnopil oblasts, it was reorganized on August 1, 1941 into [[Distrikt Galizien]] centered in Lemberg and annexed to the [[General Government]]. The area of the former Stanislav Oblast was divided into three kreis (counties): Kalusz, Stanislau, and Kolomea. On July 27, 1944 the region was liberated from the [[Nazi Germany]] by the [[Soviet Army]] (see [[Lvov\u2013Sandomierz Offensive]]).\n\nThe administrative division of Stanislav Oblast was reinstated and confirmed on January 1, 1947 with the same 36 raions and two municipalities as their existed before the war. Several settlements, however, had their status elevated. The status of a town obtained Bukachivtsi, Vyhoda, and Yaremcha, while Halych and Horodenka became recognized as cities. The next major changes in the region took place in the late 1950s. In 1957 five raions were liquidated: Vyhoda, Zhovten, Kuty, Pechenizhyn, and Chernelytsya. Then another five were liquidated in 1959: Bukachivtsi, Korshiv, Perehinske, Solotvyn, and Stanislav. On December 30, 1962 within the oblast was created the Verkhovyna Industrial Raion, centered in a town of Verkhovyna.<ref>[http://uapravo.net/akty/postanowa-main/akt8phny1h.htm \u041f\u0440\u043e \u0443\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0456\u0432 \u0456 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0434\u0435\u044f\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u043e \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0457 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0456\u0434\u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043a\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f]</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 1963 another major change took place when raions of the oblast were re-administered into the six rural raions, one \u2013 industrial, and two municipalities. There were the following administrative centers: Bohorodchany, Halych, Horodenka, Kalush, Kolomyia, Kosiv, Dolyna (municipalities \u2013 Ivano-Frankivsk (new name) and Kolomyia). On January 4, 1965 Dolyna Industrial Raion Raion was redesigned into the regular raion, while five other previous raions were recreated: Nadvirna, Rohatyn, Rozhnyativ, Snyatyn, and Tlumach. On December 8, 1966 there were created Verkhovyna and Ivano-Frankivsk raions. That was the last major re-administration of the oblast.\n\nOn March 20, 1972 in the city of Kalush was created a municipality and it became a city of oblast subordination. On December 30, 1977 the same thing happened to Yaremcha status of which was elevated as well. On March 28, 1982 the Ivano-Frankivsk Raion was re-administrated under the Tysmenytsya Raion. On October 21, 1993 the city of Bolekhiv became of an oblast subordination with its own municipality. On December 14, 2006 Yaremcha was renamed into Yaremche.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Main|Demographics of Ukraine}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;margin-left:1em;width:10%;\" align=\"right\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population<br>(''in thousands'')\n|-\n|2001\n|<center>1,406.1</center>\n|-\n|2011\n|<center>1,379.6</center>\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|Regional Administration of Statistics<ref name=\"Statistics\">{{cite web |url = http://stat.if.ukrtel.net/EX_IN/DS1.HTM |title = Main Administration of Statistics in Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast |accessdate = July 9, 2013 |publisher = Main Administration of Statistics in Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast |language = Ukrainian |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120315164829/http://stat.if.ukrtel.net/EX_IN/DS1.HTM |archivedate = March 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n|}\n\nAccording to the [[Ukrainian Census (2001)|Ukrainian Census of 2001]] most of the population consider themselves Ukrainians with a small Russian diaspora mostly located within the city of [[Ivano-Frankivsk]]. The Russian language is the dominant foreign language in the region and well understood by everyone. Among other common foreign languages are Polish, English, and German languages. The population in the region as the rest of the country was on substantial decline\n {| align=\"center\" class=\"wikitable plainlinks TablePager\"\n |+\n ! |Nationality\n ! |Number\n ! |percentage (%)\n |-----\n |[[Ukrainians]]\n |1,371,242\n |97.50\n |-----\n |[[Russians]]\n |24,925\n |1.80\n |-----\n |Others <small>([[Poles]], [[Belorussians]])</small>\n |4,532\n |0.32\n |-----\n |Total <small>(seven nationalities)</small>\n |1,406,129\n |100.00\n |+\n |}\n{{Bar box\n|width = 200px\n|float = left\n|title = <small>Ethnic composition of the region</small>\n|titlebar = #ddd\n|bars =\n{{Bar percent|[[Ukrainians]]|teal|97.5}}\n{{Bar percent|[[Russians]]|teal|1.8}}\n{{Bar percent|[[Poles]]|teal|1|0.1%}}\n{{Bar percent|[[Belarusians]]|teal|1|0.1%}}\n{{Bar percent|Others|teal|1|0.1%}}\n|caption = <small>Source: [http://2001.ukrcensus.gov.ua/eng/results/general/nationality/ Ethnic composition of the population of Ukraine, 2001 Census]</small>\n}}\n{| class=\"infobox\" style=\"text-align:left; width:25%; margin-left:10px; font-size:90%\"\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#e9e9e9; padding:0.3em;\" 0; line-height:1.2em;|Largest settlements in the region\n|-\n!  style=\"text-align:left; background:#f5f5f5;\"| <small>#</small> \n!  style=\"text-align:left; background:#f5f5f5;\"| [[List of cities in Ukraine|City]]\n!  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f5f5f5;\"| Population\n|- \n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 1 ||align=left | '''[[Ivano-Frankivsk]]''' || 215,288 (<small>2001</small>)\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 2 ||align=left | '''[[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]]''' || 67,887 (<small>2001</small>)\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 3 ||align=left | '''[[Kolomyia]]''' || 61,448 (<small>2001</small>) \n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 4 ||align=left | '''[[Dolyna]]''' || 20,696 (<small>2001</small>)\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 5 ||align=left | '''[[Nadvirna]]''' || 20,620 (<small>2001</small>)\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 6 ||align=left | '''[[Burshtyn]]''' || 15,182 (<small>2001</small>) \n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 7 ||align=left | '''[[Perehinske]]''' || 12,272 (<small>2001</small>) \n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 8 ||align=left | '''[[Bolekhiv]]''' || 10,590 (<small>2001</small>) \n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"| 9 ||align=left | '''[[Sniatyn]]''' || 10,210 (<small>2001</small>)\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n[[File:Hutsul - Ivano-Frankivsk region.jpg|thumb|[[Hutsuls|Hutsul]] plays trembita trumpet]]\n[[File:Hutsuls - wedding.jpg|thumb|Hutsuls in traditional dress in wedding ceremony in Vorokhta]]\n\n===Religion===\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb=right\n|caption=Religion in Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast (2015)<ref>[http://infolight.org.ua/content/religiyni-vpodobannya-naselennya-ukrayiny \"Religious preferences of the population of Ukraine\". Sociology poll by [[Razumkov Centre]], [[SOCIS]], [[Sociological group \"RATING\"|Rating]] and [[Kiev International Institute of Sociology|KIIS]] about the religious situation in Ukraine (2015)]</ref>\n|label1 = [[Eastern Catholic Churches|Eastern Catholicism]]\n|value1 = 57\n|color1 = Orchid\n|label2 = [[Eastern Orthodoxy]]\n|value2 = 35\n|color2 = DarkOrchid\n|label3 = Unaffiliated [[Christianity|Christian]]\n|value3 = 6\n|color3 = DodgerBlue\n|label4 = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n|value4 = 1\n|color4 = Turquoise\n|label5 = [[Protestantism]]\n|value5 = 1\n|color5 = Blue\n}}\nThe dominant religion in Ivano-Frankvisk Oblast is [[Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church]], professed by 57% of the population. Another 35% is [[Eastern Orthodox]] and 6% are [[nondenominational Christianity|unaffiliated]] generic [[Christians]]. Adherents of [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]] and [[Protestantism]] make up 1% of the population respectively.\n\n===Age structure===\n: ''0-14 years:'' 16.7% {{steady}} (male 118,518/female 112,130)\n: ''15-64 years:'' 69.5% {{steady}} (male 468,589/female 489,596)\n: ''65 years and over:'' 13.8% {{steady}} (male 63,324/female 126,635) (2013 official)\n\n===Median age===\n: ''total:'' 37.3 years {{increase}}\n: ''male:'' 34.7 years {{increase}}\n: ''female:'' 40.0 years {{increase}} (2013 official)\n\n==Culture and Tourism==\n[[File:Mud_volcano_Starunia_by_BIS.jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Mud volcano]] in [[Starunia]]]]\n\nIvano Frankivsk Oblast is home of numerous cultural festivals. There are numerous natural and architectural benchmarks that are scattered throughout the region.\n\nOne of the famous festivals is the Ukrainian International festival of [[ethnic music]] and [[land art]] \"Sheshory\" that usually takes place in the picturesque [[Hutsul]] village of the [[Kosiv Raion]] Sheshory since 2003.<ref>[http://sheshory.ua/index.html Shehsory festival] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809063723/http://sheshory.ua/index.html |date=2011-08-09 }} {{in lang|uk}}</ref> From 2007, however the festival has spread throughout the country taking place in [[Podillya]], [[Kiev Oblast]], and other places. In August 2010 the village of Spas in the [[Kolomyia Raion]] hosted a culinary event ''Smachny Spas'' in association with \"Sheshory\", while in July of the same year another eco-cultural event ''[[Trypilske kolo]]'' in the [[Rzhyschiv]] city of [[Kiev region]].\n\nThe city of [[Ivano-Frankivsk]] hosts several other festivals such as the All-Ukrainian festival of art collectives \"Carpathian Spring\" that takes place every May. Every two year the festival of modern art \"Impreza\" takes place every other year. Every odd year the city hosts the festival national-patriotic music and poetry \"Freedom\". Since May 2001 every year the city of Ivano-Frankivsk is the capital of the European blacksmith movement hosting the \"Festival of blacksmith\" and the art exhibition \"Ornamental Forging\" that takes place at the Mickewicz Square and neighboring Andrei Sheptytsky Square in city's [[old town]].\n\nOn the territory of Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast are located numerous monuments of architectural heritage. On February 8, 1994 near the city of [[Halych]] was established the National preserve '''\"Ancient Halych\"'''.<ref>[http://www.davniyhalych.if.ua/ \u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 Ancient Halych] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116131839/http://www.davniyhalych.if.ua/ |date=2010-01-16 }}</ref> Among other important sites in the region is the Church of the Holy Spirit located in the city of [[Rohatyn]] as well as the '''[[Manyava]] [[Skete]]''' near the village of Manyava in [[Bohorodchany Raion]]. The oblast also accounts for some number of various wooden churches of [[Boykos]] and [[Hutsuls]] traditional architecture.\n\nIn the [[Dolyna Raion]] (western region) visitors can find the '''Carpathian Train''' that still uses the [[narrow gauge railway]] system. Train is used for its direct purpose transporting wood as well as for a tourist recreation. The biggest benchmark of the region is the '''[[Hoverla]]''' mountain, the tallest in the nation. However, due to increased touristic activities in the post-Soviet times the mountain is a subject to a high degree of pollution. No less interesting destination serve the '''[[Dovbush rocks]]''' that are located near the city of [[Bolekhiv]] in mountains. That location was a base of an anti-Polish Peasant movement. Near the [[Manyava Skete]] is located the highest waterfall in [[Ukraine]], the '''[[Maniava waterfall]]''' (20m). In the same [[Bohorodchany Raion]] visitors may find the local '''[[mud volcano]]''' located near the village of [[Starunia]]. It was noticed for the first time in 1977 after an earthquake that took place in [[Romania]].\n[[File:\u041c\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0430\u0434 \u043f\u0456\u0441\u043b\u044f \u0434\u043e\u0449\u0443.jpg|border|thumb|203x203px|[[Maniava waterfall]]]]\n[[Bukovel]] ski resort, centralized around the village of [[Polianytsia]], on the ridge-lines of the [[Carpathian Mountains|Carpathian]] Mountain range at an elevation of 900m (3,000ft) represents a major all seasons tourist destination in the region. It is one of the most popular ski resorts in Eastern Europe and in 2012 was named the fastest growing ski resort in the world. Bukovel consists of 16 ski lifts with approximately 50 kilometers of [[Piste|pistes]]. As well as skiing visitors to the resort can enjoy 7 world class hotels, chalets with swimming pools and saunas, as well as numerous other recreational activities ranging from family friendly leisurely activities to extreme sports. During the warmer months the resort boasts cross-country and downhill mountain biking trails. Over 6,000 people visit the resort every year.\n\n==Historical and Cultural Sites==\n\n* Recently, a monument of cultural heritage was erected in the city of [[Kolomyya]] in Pokuttya. The [[Pysanka Museum|museum ''\"Pysanka\"'']] was built in 2000 and is the only one in the world.\n* Another interesting historical site is the cavern complex in the [[Dovbush Rock]]. The site is dedicated to the legendary freedom fighter [[Oleksa Dovbush]] who in the legend fights against the Polish [[szlachta]]. The rock complex is located about {{convert|7|mi|0|abbr=out}} south west from [[Bolekhiv]] near village of [[Bubnysche]].\n* The [[Church of the Holy Spirit (Rohatyn)|Church of the Holy Spirit]], built in 1598, is located in the north of the Oblast in the small city of [[Rohatyn]].\n\n===Popular culture===\nIn 1979 [[Sofia Rotaru]] performed the song \"Krai\" (''[Native] Land'') about ''[[Prykarpattia]]''.<ref>{{YouTube|MmLh0laIlug|Krai by Rotaru}}</ref> In the song Rotaru calls ''Prykarpattia'' the land of the [[Cheremosh]] and [[Prut]] rivers.\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Roads===\n;State Highways\nThrough Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast runs one European route <small>{{jct|country=EUR|E|50 }}</small> which travels through the city of [[Rohatyn]] in the north. It coincides with the Ukrainian International highway <small>{{Road marker simple|Highway M12 (Ukraine)|M12|blue|white|white}}</small> which is the only highway of that classification in the region. The highway travels from [[Zhydachiv]] in [[Lviv Oblast]] and after passing Rohatyn travels towards [[Berezhany]] in [[Ternopil Oblast]].\n\nBeside that highway, through the region runs three Ukrainian National highways of nationwide importance.\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway H09 (Ukraine)|H09|blue|white|white}} traveling from [[Lviv]] the route enters the region from the north near Rohatyn and after passesing the cities of [[Ivano-Frankivsk]] and [[Yaremcha]] continues on towards [[Rakhiv]] going over the [[Carpathian]] ridge.\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway H10 (Ukraine)|H10|blue|white|white}} which starts in [[Stryi]] also passes Ivano-Frankivsk and through [[Kolomyia]] and [[Sniatyn]] continues on towards [[Chernivtsi]].\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway H18 (Ukraine)|H18|blue|white|white}} starts from the center of Ivano-Frnkivsk and through [[Tysmenytsia]] (Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast) and [[Monastyryska]] ([[Ternopil Oblast]]) terminates in [[Ternopil]].\n\nThere is also small network of minor P-highways.\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway P20 (Ukraine)|P20|white|black|black}} runs from Tyaziv (north of Ivano-Frankivsk) through [[Tlumach]] and [[Horodenka]] to [[Sniatyn]].\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway P21 (Ukraine)|P21|white|black|black}} runs from [[Dolyna]] over the [[Carpathian]] to [[Khust]] ([[Zakarpattia Oblast]]).\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway P24 (Ukraine)|P24|white|black|black}} runs from Tatariv ([[Yaremche municipality]]) to [[Verkhovyna]], [[Kosiv]], [[Kolomyia]], [[Hvizdets]], [[Horodenka]], and [[Ternopil Oblast]].\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway P38 (Ukraine)|P38|white|black|black}} runs from [[Bohorodchany]] to the village of [[Stara Huta, Bohorodchany Raion|Stara Huta]].\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway P62 (Ukraine)|P62|white|black|black}} runs from Verkhniy Yaseniv ([[Verkhovyna Raion]]) to Usteriky, then by the [[Prut]] valley and the [[Chernivtsi Oblast]] border travels to [[Kuty]] where it turns into Chernivtsi Oblast towards [[Storozhynets]].\n;Regional Highways\nT-network (09)\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0901 (Ukraine)|T0901|white|black|black}} - [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]], Yasen, Kuzmynets\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0902 (Ukraine)|T0902|white|black|black}} - [[Borshniv-Osada]], [[Rozhniativ]], Kosmach, [[Nadvirna]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0903 (Ukraine)|T0903|white|black|black}} - [[Halych]], Medukha, Zastavche, [[Pidhaitsi]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0904 (Ukraine)|T0904|white|black|black}} - Ozeryany, [[Obertyn]], [[Hvizdets]], Zabolotiv, Rozhniv, [[Kuty]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0905 (Ukraine)|T0905|white|black|black}} - [[Delyatyn]], [[Lanchyn]], [[Kolomyia]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0906 (Ukraine)|T0906|white|black|black}} - [[Ivano-Frankivsk]], Cherniiv, [[Nadvirna]], Bystrytsia\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0909 (Ukraine)|T0909|white|black|black}} - [[Kosiv]], Rozhniv, [[Sniatyn]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0910 (Ukraine)|T0910|white|black|black}} - [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]], [[Burshtyn]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0911 (Ukraine)|T0911|white|black|black}} - [[Bolekhiv]], Tysiv, Kozakivka\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T0915 (Ukraine)|T0915|white|black|black}} - Pistyn, Mykytyntsi, Verkhniy Verbizh\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T1417 (Ukraine)|T1417|white|black|black}} - (Lviv Oblast) Kurovychi, [[Peremyshlyany]], [[Rohatyn]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T1419 (Ukraine)|T1419|white|black|black}} - (Lviv Oblast) [[Kalush, Ukraine|Kalush]], [[Zhuravno]], [[Zhydachiv]], Rozdil, Mykolaiv\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T2601 (Ukraine)|T2601|white|black|black}} - (Chernivtsi Oblast) / (Romanian border) (route 209G) Seliatyn, Parkulyna, Dykhtynets, Marynychi, Pidzakharychi, [[Kuty]], Sloboda Banyliv, Chortoryia, Hlynytsia, [[Chernivtsi]]\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T2621 (Ukraine)|T2621|white|black|black}} - (Chernivtsi Oblast) [[Horodenka]], Khreshchatyk\n*{{Road marker simple|Highway T2648 (Ukraine)|T2648|white|black|black}} - (Chernivtsi Oblast) Vyzhnytsia, [[Kuty]], Pidzakharychi\n\n==Notable people==\nPeople born in ''[[Prykarpattya]]'' include the historical figures (heroes) [[Yaroslav Osmomysl]], [[Roxelana]], [[Semen Vysochan]] and [[Oleksa Dovbush]]; writers [[Mariyka Pidhiryanka]], [[Vasyl Stefanyk]], [[Les Martynovych]], [[Ivan Vahylevych]], [[Marko Cheremshyna]], [[Man\u00e8s Sperber]],  artist Svyatoslav Hordynsky (founder of the Association of Independent Ukrainian Artists); leaders of the Ukrainian liberation movement [[Stepan Bandera]] and [[Dmytro Vitovsky]]; opera singer Maria Stefyuk, singer [[Mika Newton]], poet [[Dmytro Pavlychko]], and many others.\n\nToday's city of Ivano-Frankivsk was home to the Potocki family of Polish high nobles (magnates). The \"Great Hetman of the Crown\" [[J\u00f3zef Potocki]] was born in what was then Stanis\u0142aw\u00f3w.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]'s [[Stanis\u0142aw\u00f3w Voivodeship]] (1921\u20131939)\n*[[List of Canadian place names of Ukrainian origin]] \u2013 [[Ukrainian Canadian|Ukrainian immigrants to Canada]] brought place names from this oblast to [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Alberta]]; a few [[one-room schools]] had names of villages from this region.\n*[[Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast local election, 2006]]\n*[[List of heads of government in Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast and Stanislawow Voivodeship]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{cite book|last=\u0411\u0430\u043a\u0438\u043d, \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|title=\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0440\u043f\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0435, \u043f\u0443\u0442\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a|year=1980|publisher=\u0418\u0437\u0434-\u0432\u043e \"\u041a\u0430\u0440\u043f\u0430\u0442\u044b\"|pages=253|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=yTdbUIe5NZHc8wTd3IHgAw&id=aWYKAQAAIAAJ|display-authors=etal}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.if.gov.ua/ Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast official site]\n* [http://www.orada.if.ua/index.php?id=home Oblast council official site] {{in lang|uk}}\n* [http://www.jewishgalicia.net \"JewishGalicia.net\" \u2013 Jewish history in the Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170310050048/http://www.knowbysight.info/1_ukra/00125.asp Handbook on history of Communist Party and Soviet Union]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110702235540/http://whp057.narod.ru/iv-fra.htm History of the region]\n* [http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=3%ED-06 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0412\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0443  \u0441\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0443  \u0422\u043b\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0446\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0443 \u041a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433